,"about 1390":"circa 1390","1374":"1374","1351":"1351","1350":"1350","1391":"1391","1390":"1390","1415":"1415","about 1417":"circa 1417","1457":"1457","about 1415":"circa 1415","1422":"1422","1453":"1453","about 1414":"circa 1414","1452":"1452","1417":"1417","after 1422":"na 1422","Holme Pierrepont, Nottinghamshire, England":"Holme Pierrepont, Nottinghamshire, England"},"en":{"about 1390–1452":"about 1390–1452","1374–Female":"1374–Deceased","1390–1452":"1390–1452","1391–1453":"1391–1453","1415–1457":"1415–1457","1417–Male":"1417–Deceased","1350–1422":"1350–1422","1351–Female":"1351–Deceased","about 1370":"about 1370","about 1390":"about 1390","1374":"1374","1351":"1351","1350":"1350","1391":"1391","1390":"1390","1415":"1415","about 1417":"about 1417","1457":"1457","about 1415":"about 1415","1422":"1422","1453":"1453","about 1414":"about 1414","1452":"1452","1417":"1417","after 1422":"after 1422","Holme Pierrepont, Nottinghamshire, England":"Holme Pierrepont, Nottinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pierrepont","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: variant of   Pierpoint  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Pierpoint","meanings":["English: variant of   Pierpont  ."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>George</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Henry Pierrepont was born about 1390, in Holme Pierrepont, Nottinghamshire, England, his father, Sir Edmund Pierrepont, was 42 and his mother, Frances Franke, was 41. He married Ellen Langford about 1414. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1452, in his hometown, at the age of 63."},"et":{"about 1390–1452":"umbes 1390–1452","1374–Female":"1374–Surnud","1390–1452":"1390–1452","1391–1453":"1391–1453","1415–1457":"1415–1457","1417–Male":"1417–Surnud","1350–1422":"1350–1422","1351–Female":"1351–Surnud","about 1370":"umbes 1370","about 1390":"umbes 1390","1374":"1374","1351":"1351","1350":"1350","1391":"1391","1390":"1390","1415":"1415","about 1417":"umbes 1417","1457":"1457","about 1415":"umbes 1415","1422":"1422","1453":"1453","about 1414":"umbes 1414"